PART 6: WHY dc3+dc5=3 IS IMPOSSIBLE AT n=6
======================================================================
  Score sequences with dc3=3 at n=6:
    (0, 2, 2, 3, 4, 4): dc5 ∈ [1]
    (1, 1, 2, 3, 3, 5): dc5 ∈ [1]

  Score sequences with dc3=2 at n=6:
    (0, 1, 3, 3, 4, 4): dc5 ∈ [0]
    (0, 2, 2, 3, 3, 5): dc5 ∈ [0]
    (1, 1, 1, 4, 4, 4): dc5 ∈ [0]
    (1, 1, 2, 2, 4, 5): dc5 ∈ [0]

  CONCLUSION AT n=6:
  dc3=3 at n=6 ALWAYS has dc5=1 (minimum).
  dc3≤2 at n=6 ALWAYS has dc5=0.
  So dc3+dc5=3 requires dc3=3, dc5=0 — IMPOSSIBLE.
  Same mechanism as n=5!

